		<hr size="1">Thank you for the reply, Spiddles.</P><P>The 1k Heal is in the game now, but at lvl 60. In my eyes it is way too late. I use my heals to keep casters - also Clerics - alive or to cover heals while the Cleric casts CH, so I would need it earlier.</P><P>Most people call for another class that can do the job if no Cleric is available and I surely understand the concerns of Clerics if another class gets their skills. The topic is indeed difficult, that's the reason why VI struggles so much, as I see it.</P><P>I will take a short view on other classes: Magician, Necromancer and Shaman.</P><P>All three classes have two skills, Pets and tremendous damage in battle, aside of that some other skills. Now if you want pets and damage a group can choose from either of these three, their choice will only depend on whether they need a backup healer, a "manabattery" or some summonend items (reducing the classes on those skills for now).</P><P>In the areas Crowdcontrol, Healing, Buffing and Rezzing - to a minor degree also tanking and damagedealing - the groups have only one intelligent choice each: Enchanter, Cleric and Warrior.<BR>Why can't two players of certain classes (Druid + Shaman, Ranger + Shadow Knight or Paladin + Bard) be at least 150% as effective as one player of a specialist class? Concerning to the posts of highlevels on the various boards, they aren't.<BR>Nevertheless, versatility is being said to be a viable strength of Hybrids, so one can say cummulation of skills is the viable strength of the specialist classes.</P><P>I allmost would say that it'd be fair if one class each surpasses the Cleric one of their skills each: One better healer, one better buffer and one better Rezzer, but those three classes lack strongly in the other two skills or don't own them at all.<BR>Same goes for Warriors, at least one class is better in tanking and at least one class is better in toe-to-toe damage dealing (as it is now).<BR>Please don't consider this a flame, it only represents some thoughts - free to discuss.</P><P>This is the situation from a Druid's perspective, I knew what expected me when I chose the class, so this is no whining:</P><P>We can DoT and DD - Wizards, Mages, Shamans and Necromancers are better<BR>We can heal - Clerics are better<BR>We can buff - Clerics and Shamans are better<BR>We can gate - Wizards have more destinations</P><P>I will not list the rest like pets, root and so on. We are Jack-of-all-trades and masters in none, so it is ok.</P><P>For a Warrior the situation looks like this: They are best tanks but there are two classes that can deal more damage. These are Rogue and Monk and both have also other skills to offer. A Cleric has no superior class in either of his skills, while there are three classes that would only need an enhancement of the existing abilities.</P><P>Thinking about it, I could see <BR>- a Paladin rezzing better then a Cleric<BR>- a Shaman coming close to the healing abilities of a Cleric (lets say a heal for 1.5k to 2k HP with 8 seconds casting time)<BR>- a Druid with the 1k heal at 55 and strongly increased damageshields<BR>- a Cleric with the best buffs in the game, as it is now</P><P>let me invent some numbers:</P><P>A Cleric can Rez 100% (not XP, this is just a measurement), heal 100% and buff 100%.<BR>A Paladin would Rez 125%, heal 25% and buff 50% as good as a Cleric, has some other skills.<BR>A Shaman would Rez 75%, heal 75% and buff 75% and has other skills.<BR>A Druid would Rez 0%, heal 50% and buff 75% and has other skills.</P><P>I don't see a too deep impact on Clerics in the 50+ game - not saying that I overlook something. However I see a big increase for the other classes. And most important I am not giving superpower to my class, I would - as I said - increase other skills to make them more group friendly. Shamans and Paladins would have a fairly good standing though (hell, I am happy that I don't need to do this for all classes, poor VI, hehe).</P><P>Fey<br>&nbsp;